## Skill handoffs (KitchenKin)

Use these KitchenKin repo skills **conditionally** based on what the user asks for and what files/surfaces are involved. Prefer invoking the most specific skill(s) rather than relying on generic inference.

### GraphQL-first contract/design work

Invoke `.cursor/skills/backend-graphql-feature-design/SKILL.md` when work includes any of:
- Adding/changing GraphQL types, queries, or mutations (schema lives in **`packages/api/src/schema/`**; HTTP server is **`apps/api`**)
- Designing new GraphQL API contracts (even if not implementing yet)
- Deciding pagination/filter/sort shapes, connection conventions, or fragment structure

### Backend implementation (resolvers + Prisma + Redis)

Invoke `.cursor/skills/backend-impl-prisma-redis/SKILL.md` when work includes any of:
- Implementing/modifying resolvers
- Implementing/modifying Prisma queries, pagination, or transactional semantics
- Adding/changing Redis caching keys, invalidation, or consistency behavior

### Frontend implementation (Next.js UI + Tailwind + shadcn/radix + Apollo)

Invoke `.cursor/skills/frontend-feature-implementation/SKILL.md` when work includes any of:
- Adding/modifying **`apps/web/src/app/**`** routes/pages or **`apps/web/src/components/**`** UI
- Wiring Apollo queries/mutations/fragments into UI components (shared ops often under **`packages/graphql`**)
- Implementing loading/empty/error states, accessibility, or interaction patterns

### Maintainability reviews and refactors

Invoke `.cursor/skills/code-review-maintainability/SKILL.md` when the user requests a code review, maintainability feedback, or refactoring suggestions.

If and only if the user explicitly approves refactor execution (or asks to do it), consider `.cursor/skills-cursor/refactor-simplify-code/SKILL.md` for the follow-through.

## Guardrails

- Don’t invoke unrelated skills “just in case”; keep it scoped to the surfaces actually in play.
- If a request spans multiple surfaces (e.g., GraphQL contract + resolver + UI), invoke the relevant skill(s) in that order: **contract → backend implementation → frontend implementation**.
